uffolk): from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Godebald</i>, <i>Godbaud</i>, a medieval French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Godebald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i> ‘god’ + <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’."],"variants":[{"name":"Godbolt","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Godbold  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"George Godbold was born in 1401, in Dennington, Suffolk, England. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Elizabeth Sheldrake. He died in 1450, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1401–1450":"1401–1450","1401–1430":"1401–1430","1423–1507":"1423–1507","1425–1507":"1425–1507","–Female":"Surnud","1425":"1425","1401":"1401","1423":"1423","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","after 1430":"pär